1
00:00:21,021 --> 00:00:23,649
Hello, there.
I bet you're already saying to yourself:

2
00:00:23,857 --> 00:00:26,018
"Oh, I've already seen this one.

3
00:00:26,226 --> 00:00:29,007
Another holiday special narrated
by some new teen star...

4
00:00:29,295 --> 00:00:33,288
...between takes of their oh-so-popular
new sitcom series."

5
00:00:33,500 --> 00:00:37,994
Well, I'm here to tell you,
"Not this time," because I'm not a star.

6
00:00:38,204 --> 00:00:40,263
Well, not yet at least.

7
00:00:40,473 --> 00:00:42,873
And this ain't about how
so-and-so saved Christmas...

8
00:00:43,076 --> 00:00:44,668
...for all the good boys and girls.

9
00:00:44,878 --> 00:00:47,779
It's more about Santa Claus
settling some unfinished business...

10
00:00:47,981 --> 00:00:50,074
...with a very old acquaintance...

11
00:00:50,283 --> 00:00:53,582
...and some kids who
accidentally destroy Christmas.

12
00:00:53,787 --> 00:00:56,483
That's right, nothing under the trees.

13
00:00:56,689 --> 00:00:59,123
A catastrophe caused by a kid... Me.

14
00:00:59,325 --> 00:01:01,520
- that was too smart for his own good.

15
00:01:01,728 --> 00:01:05,391
A kid who messed up his hometown,
messed with Santa...

16
00:01:05,598 --> 00:01:10,695
...messed with Christmas, and the
entire, complete known universe...

17
00:01:10,904 --> 00:01:14,465
...or at least,
it almost worked out that way.

18
00:01:14,674 --> 00:01:17,336
So grab yourself a
super-sized hot chocolate...

19
00:01:17,544 --> 00:01:20,775
...sit back, relax, and enjoy the ride...

20
00:01:20,980 --> 00:01:23,380
...because this is one
very special Christmas...

21
00:01:23,583 --> 00:01:26,017
...you're never gonna forget.

22
00:03:51,764 --> 00:03:55,200
So, Veronica, looks like another
green Christmas this year.

23
00:03:55,401 --> 00:03:58,131
Sure does, Trevor. Your turn.

24
00:04:04,911 --> 00:04:06,742
So, Veronica, hey.

25
00:04:06,946 --> 00:04:09,176
I asked Santa for a
new chess set this year.

26
00:04:14,320 --> 00:04:16,185
Okay.
Well, what did you ask him for?

27
00:04:17,690 --> 00:04:19,021
Nothing, Trevor.

28
00:04:19,225 --> 00:04:21,455
I don't believe in Santa Claus.

29
00:04:21,661 --> 00:04:23,822
For real life? Come on.

30
00:04:26,132 --> 00:04:28,498
Sorry, Trev. It's the skeptic in me.

31
00:04:29,636 --> 00:04:32,366
I tend not to believe
in things I can't see.

32
00:04:33,206 --> 00:04:37,267
Veronica, you don't have to
see him to believe he's real.

33
00:04:37,477 --> 00:04:40,412
Let me get this straight.
You believe in an overweight guy...

34
00:04:40,613 --> 00:04:44,606
...who rides around in a sleigh
pulled by "magic flying reindeer"?

35
00:04:44,817 --> 00:04:46,546
Well, basically, yeah.

36
00:04:46,753 --> 00:04:50,746
Trevor, Trevor, Trevor.
Think about it.

37
00:04:51,124 --> 00:04:53,490
There are two billion
children in the world.

38
00:04:53,693 --> 00:04:54,785
So, what's the problem?

39
00:04:54,994 --> 00:04:57,485
Even if he's only giving
presents to a third of them...

40
00:04:57,697 --> 00:05:00,723
...Santa's sleigh would have to
go 3,000 times the speed of sound.

41
00:05:00,933 --> 00:05:01,922
Carry on.

42
00:05:02,135 --> 00:05:04,865
Assuming each child gets
one medium-sized present...

43
00:05:05,071 --> 00:05:07,301
...that weighs an average
half a kilogram.

44
00:05:07,507 --> 00:05:09,998
The sleigh is carrying
400,000 metric tons...

45
00:05:10,209 --> 00:05:12,143
...or the average weight
of an ocean liner.

46
00:05:12,345 --> 00:05:13,903
Did you read this on the internet?

47
00:05:14,113 --> 00:05:19,016
On land, conventional reindeer
can pull no more than 150 kilograms...

48
00:05:19,218 --> 00:05:23,780
...even granting that flying reindeer
could pull 10 times the normal amount.

49
00:05:23,990 --> 00:05:27,756
Well, I don't know how to
break this to you, Trevor...

50
00:05:28,594 --> 00:05:30,289
...but it all sounds rather unlikely.

51
00:05:30,496 --> 00:05:32,361
Interesting theory, Veronica.

52
00:05:32,565 --> 00:05:35,966
Bravo, but Santa doesn't
ride the scientific wave.

53
00:05:36,169 --> 00:05:37,227
He's magical.

54
00:05:38,004 --> 00:05:40,029
Whatever.

55
00:05:40,506 --> 00:05:43,134
By the way, checkmate.

56
00:05:43,343 --> 00:05:45,573
A most dramatic game as usual,
Gabriel.

57
00:05:45,778 --> 00:05:48,906
Yes, Errol.
My heart is still racing.

58
00:06:02,662 --> 00:06:04,857
Trevor, I have one question.

59
00:06:05,064 --> 00:06:08,625
Just curious, what was all that talk about
Santa Claus during the chess match?

60
00:06:08,835 --> 00:06:10,826
Yeah, oh, what up with that, T?

61
00:06:11,037 --> 00:06:12,902
You ruined a perfectly
good tournament.

62
00:06:13,106 --> 00:06:14,573
I was trying to head fake her.

63
00:06:14,774 --> 00:06:16,867
Get her off her game, you know,
distract her.

64
00:06:17,076 --> 00:06:18,304
Distract her?

65
00:06:18,511 --> 00:06:21,571
- Trevor, you lost the game.
- It only looks that way.

66
00:06:23,216 --> 00:06:24,410
Excuse me. Hey, Ronnie!

67
00:06:26,119 --> 00:06:28,019
You dropped something.

68
00:06:28,454 --> 00:06:29,887
Allow me.

69
00:06:30,957 --> 00:06:32,322
You know what your problem is?

70
00:06:34,927 --> 00:06:36,827
You don't believe in magic.

71
00:06:37,029 --> 00:06:39,020
It's in your other hand.

72
00:06:39,232 --> 00:06:42,292
- True. But what if it wasn't?
- Trevor.

73
00:06:42,502 --> 00:06:44,970
Can't we just agree
to disagree sometimes?

74
00:06:45,171 --> 00:06:46,331
Okay, Veronica.

75
00:06:46,539 --> 00:06:48,769
But I know Santa is real.
I know it in my heart.

76
00:06:48,975 --> 00:06:51,671
It's probably just heartburn.

77
00:06:51,878 --> 00:06:53,812
Very funny.

78
00:06:56,616 --> 00:06:59,983
Cuddles, the rainbow
unicorn sparkle wand.

79
00:07:01,454 --> 00:07:03,251
What are you looking at?

80
00:07:03,456 --> 00:07:04,445
Oh, nothing.

81
00:07:04,657 --> 00:07:07,990
You know, I was thinking. What if
I could prove to you Santa is real?

82
00:07:08,194 --> 00:07:11,129
- Prove it? How?
- With physical evidence.

83
00:07:11,330 --> 00:07:14,356
- Physical evidence of Santa Claus?
- Exactly.

84
00:07:14,567 --> 00:07:19,368
All I have to do is, well, catch him.

85
00:07:19,572 --> 00:07:21,563
You know, so you can
see him for yourself.

86
00:07:21,774 --> 00:07:23,332
Well, that's great.

87
00:07:23,543 --> 00:07:25,443
Too bad he doesn't exist.

88
00:07:26,813 --> 00:07:31,944
<i>I believe in Santa Claus</i>

89
00:07:32,151 --> 00:07:35,211
<i>Because he's true to me</i>

90
00:07:38,391 --> 00:07:42,589
<i>There's no way</i>
<i>That reindeer and a sleigh</i>

91
00:07:42,795 --> 00:07:46,629
<i>Can take a man on such a jolly spree</i>

92
00:07:48,501 --> 00:07:53,200
<i>Stop right now</i>
<i>Let me show you how</i>

93
00:07:53,406 --> 00:07:57,843
<i>He can do this all in one night</i>

94
00:08:00,146 --> 00:08:03,809
<i>There's no way</i>
<i>It's impossible</i>

95
00:08:04,750 --> 00:08:09,153
<i>The facts will never prove you right</i>

96
00:08:10,990 --> 00:08:14,391
You know, Veronica,
thanks to the different time zones...

97
00:08:14,594 --> 00:08:18,997
...if Santa travels east to west,
he buys himself approximately 31 hours...

98
00:08:19,198 --> 00:08:24,431
...of Christmas Eve to work with,
not merely 12 as in your flawed critique.

99
00:08:24,637 --> 00:08:26,400
Nice try, Trevor...

100
00:08:26,606 --> 00:08:30,167
...but I'm afraid your numbers
are just like your name...

101
00:08:30,743 --> 00:08:34,941
...mechanically correct,
but unsophisticated.

102
00:08:35,147 --> 00:08:39,550
<i>These are all just silly words</i>

103
00:08:41,521 --> 00:08:44,513
<i>I need to see some proof</i>

104
00:08:45,558 --> 00:08:47,082
<i>Just close your eyes</i>

105
00:08:48,494 --> 00:08:50,257
<i>And you will hear</i>

106
00:08:52,398 --> 00:08:55,231
<i>The reindeer on the roof</i>

107
00:08:57,136 --> 00:09:01,334
<i>There's no way</i>
<i>That this Santa Claus</i>

108
00:09:02,575 --> 00:09:06,443
<i>Can do it all on Christmas Eve</i>

109
00:09:07,847 --> 00:09:12,216
<i>Anything is possible</i>

110
00:09:12,818 --> 00:09:17,221
<i>As long as we believe</i>

111
00:09:18,457 --> 00:09:26,091
<i>The facts will never prove you right</i>

112
00:09:27,233 --> 00:09:30,293
In fact, why am I even
having this discussion?

113
00:09:32,071 --> 00:09:35,040
Errol, Gabriel,
you believe in Santa, right?

114
00:09:35,241 --> 00:09:39,177
We avoid taking a
stance on such things.

115
00:09:40,446 --> 00:09:43,415
In metaphysics,
one prefers to remain on the fence.

116
00:09:43,616 --> 00:09:47,382
- But you'll help me catch him?
- Oh, baby, yeah.

117
00:09:47,587 --> 00:09:49,145
Okay, guys, we've got work to do.

118
00:09:49,355 --> 00:09:51,880
Our first order of business
is gathering data.

119
00:09:52,091 --> 00:09:53,683
So where do we find the big guy?

120
00:10:13,446 --> 00:10:15,505
Main generator's up.

121
00:10:16,682 --> 00:10:18,206
Main generator's up.

122
00:10:18,417 --> 00:10:21,011
Solar batteries and
borealis tranjector.

123
00:10:24,190 --> 00:10:26,886
Solar batteries and
borealis tranjector.

124
00:10:29,629 --> 00:10:30,618
Closing the doors.

125
00:10:31,097 --> 00:10:33,361
Close hangar doors.

126
00:10:39,739 --> 00:10:42,401
That's 10 seconds faster than last year,
sir.

127
00:10:42,608 --> 00:10:43,973
<i>Stand down from drill.</i>

128
00:10:44,176 --> 00:10:46,576
<i>Reindeer wranglers report to the barn.</i>

129
00:10:46,779 --> 00:10:48,679
Good work, team.
You guys are the best.

130
00:10:48,881 --> 00:10:51,179
Now, how about that coffee?

131
00:10:51,384 --> 00:10:54,785
Your mocha-double-cappuccino-
yummalicious-delicious-yuletide decaf...

132
00:10:54,987 --> 00:10:56,454
...shaken not stirred, sir?

133
00:10:56,656 --> 00:10:59,853
<i>Two-one-three, report to main office.</i>

134
00:11:00,059 --> 00:11:02,653
Soy milk? Who put soy milk in my...?

135
00:11:02,862 --> 00:11:05,990
You know what the doctor says,
my little Santa Wanta.

136
00:11:06,198 --> 00:11:07,893
Yes, dear.

137
00:11:08,801 --> 00:11:10,769
<i>Elf 36, call your mother.</i>

138
00:11:10,970 --> 00:11:12,904
- Hand it over.
- What are you getting at?

139
00:11:13,105 --> 00:11:15,300
Come on.

140
00:11:15,508 --> 00:11:16,566
And the other one.

141
00:11:16,776 --> 00:11:18,710
<i>Beware of rabid reindeer.</i>

142
00:11:21,280 --> 00:11:24,374
I've got my eye on you, Mr. Claus.

143
00:11:26,318 --> 00:11:29,446
Back to work, everyone.
We're on a schedule here.

144
00:11:30,256 --> 00:11:34,454
Okay, start loading the presents,
people. Stat.

145
00:11:35,394 --> 00:11:37,589
- Let's get going.
- Yes, sir.

146
00:11:40,933 --> 00:11:43,299
- Ribbons and bows, come on.
- Ribbons and bows!

147
00:11:43,502 --> 00:11:44,526
Wrapping paper!

148
00:11:44,737 --> 00:11:46,637
More presents!

149
00:12:01,687 --> 00:12:04,520
Merry Christmas.

150
00:12:05,391 --> 00:12:08,656
- Is it 4:00 yet?
- Three more hours, Frank.

151
00:12:08,861 --> 00:12:12,058
Oh, boy.

152
00:12:20,806 --> 00:12:23,240
Merry Christmas.

153
00:12:23,442 --> 00:12:26,275
Merry, merry, merry Christmas.

154
00:12:32,618 --> 00:12:35,143
And precisely what are we doing here,
Trevor?

155
00:12:35,354 --> 00:12:38,482
Veronica doesn't believe in magic.
We'll use science to catch him.

156
00:12:38,691 --> 00:12:42,525
First we'll need some real
evidence from our specimen.

157
00:12:43,462 --> 00:12:45,930
Why don't we just spirit
the gentleman away right now?

158
00:12:46,132 --> 00:12:47,861
First we have to confirm his identity.

159
00:12:48,067 --> 00:12:51,059
You know, make sure he's the
real McCoy. Did you guys bring it?

160
00:12:51,270 --> 00:12:53,761
Check. The X-ray 9,000.

161
00:12:53,973 --> 00:12:58,205
- It's never been tested outside the lab.
- I hope he's got lead in his underwear.

162
00:13:03,082 --> 00:13:04,481
Come on up here, young fella.

163
00:13:05,351 --> 00:13:07,945
Now, what would you like
for Christmas this year?

164
00:13:08,154 --> 00:13:12,284
- Well, actually, just a few photos of you.
- Well, of course.

165
00:13:12,491 --> 00:13:16,052
- Jill, take a picture.
- That won't be necessary.

166
00:13:16,262 --> 00:13:19,197
I brought my own photographers.

167
00:13:20,065 --> 00:13:22,397
Hey, look, a rainbow.

168
00:13:24,136 --> 00:13:25,398
DNA, check.

169
00:13:25,604 --> 00:13:26,593
Visual reference...

170
00:13:29,909 --> 00:13:31,171
...check.
- Well...

171
00:13:31,377 --> 00:13:35,040
...he has an enormous solid mass of
polyester padding in the thorax region.

172
00:13:35,247 --> 00:13:38,444
And he's wearing a rudimentary beard
of some unknown fibrous origin.

173
00:13:38,651 --> 00:13:40,050
Prepare yourself, Trevor.

174
00:13:42,021 --> 00:13:44,990
That man in the town
square is not Santa Claus.

175
00:13:46,559 --> 00:13:49,255
Well how do we find the real Santa?

176
00:13:49,461 --> 00:13:51,861
Gentlemen, to the Internet.

177
00:13:54,934 --> 00:13:57,368
Looking for Santa Claus, Kris Kringle.

178
00:13:57,570 --> 00:13:58,696
Saint Nicholas.

179
00:13:58,904 --> 00:14:00,337
- Father Christmas.
- Cinder Claus.

180
00:14:00,539 --> 00:14:03,007
- Papa Noël.
- Père Noël.

181
00:14:03,909 --> 00:14:05,877
- Veronica?
- Veronica?

182
00:14:06,078 --> 00:14:08,069
Who calls him that?

183
00:14:08,280 --> 00:14:10,145
Have you been there all along?

184
00:14:10,349 --> 00:14:12,943
Come on, guys,
you're wasting your time.

185
00:14:13,152 --> 00:14:17,088
It's Christmas Eve.
Let's go do something fun.

186
00:14:20,593 --> 00:14:22,925
Okay, okay, for the sake of argument...

187
00:14:23,128 --> 00:14:26,063
...what if I can see that
perhaps Santa maybe exists...

188
00:14:26,265 --> 00:14:29,996
...in some kind of parallel,
alternate universe kind of thing?

189
00:14:31,403 --> 00:14:35,362
You're saying he lives
on another planet?

190
00:14:35,574 --> 00:14:37,667
No, I think she's saying
he has a time machine.

191
00:14:37,877 --> 00:14:40,471
No, no, no. I was just kidding.

192
00:14:40,679 --> 00:14:45,013
Look, I'm just trying to help
you see that you're acting crazy.

193
00:14:46,785 --> 00:14:50,346
All right, Veronica, you're really
starting to rain on our parade.

194
00:14:50,556 --> 00:14:52,820
But you sound ridiculous.

195
00:14:53,025 --> 00:14:54,356
Do you guys even have a plan?

196
00:14:55,394 --> 00:14:57,328
Okay, good question.

197
00:14:58,731 --> 00:15:00,756
Which one of you two
has been keeping notes?

198
00:15:01,567 --> 00:15:03,228
Well, we have a route, a velocity...

199
00:15:03,435 --> 00:15:06,029
...and a fair guesstimate
of what time he'll be overhead.

200
00:15:06,238 --> 00:15:10,197
- With a slight margin of error.
- About the size of Texas.

201
00:15:10,409 --> 00:15:12,070
That's not a plan.

202
00:15:12,278 --> 00:15:13,768
It's not even an idea.

203
00:15:13,979 --> 00:15:17,176
It's just a bunch of words strung
together trying to sound scientific.

204
00:15:17,383 --> 00:15:19,851
Maybe,
but I'm gonna catch Santa Claus...

205
00:15:20,052 --> 00:15:22,953
...and that will be all the
scientific proof you need.

206
00:15:23,155 --> 00:15:26,613
<i>Trevor, quick.</i>
<i>Come up to the observatory right away.</i>

207
00:15:39,471 --> 00:15:41,336
You know it's Christmas Eve, right?

208
00:15:42,741 --> 00:15:47,678
- New Year's Eve is still a week away.
- Oh, yes, dear, of course.

209
00:15:47,880 --> 00:15:53,341
We're celebrating because we just
spotted a very rare and unusual comet.

210
00:15:53,552 --> 00:15:56,680
It's called Lefreeze,
just a big ball of ice really.

211
00:15:56,889 --> 00:16:01,223
And it drifts close to Earth's
orbit only once every 100 years.

212
00:16:01,427 --> 00:16:03,019
Right around Christmas time.

213
00:16:03,228 --> 00:16:07,790
Wow, congratulations, Dr. Taylor.
What are you doing to celebrate?

214
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:11,299
Well, it is Christmas, you know,
and we're having dinner with grandma...

215
00:16:11,503 --> 00:16:13,835
...which reminds me,
are you coming, Trevor?

216
00:16:14,039 --> 00:16:15,472
Yeah.

217
00:16:16,041 --> 00:16:18,566
But we've kind of got that
holiday book report to do.

218
00:16:19,478 --> 00:16:21,605
- A book report on Christmas Eve?
- Yeah.

219
00:16:21,814 --> 00:16:24,078
It sort of came up at the last minute.

220
00:16:24,283 --> 00:16:25,443
Right, Errol?

221
00:16:25,651 --> 00:16:27,312
Sure, whatever you say, sir.

222
00:16:27,519 --> 00:16:30,852
Okay, Trevor, you can join us later.

223
00:16:31,056 --> 00:16:34,514
There's a casserole in the fridge
in case you kids get hungry.

224
00:16:34,893 --> 00:16:37,157
All right,
we'll make this our control center.

225
00:16:37,363 --> 00:16:41,163
- You're incorrigible, you know?
- That's what you like about me.

226
00:16:44,903 --> 00:16:47,337
So that's Lefreeze, huh?

227
00:17:17,770 --> 00:17:18,964
My back.

228
00:17:19,171 --> 00:17:23,369
- How long have I been asleep?
- A hundred years, Mr. Lefreeze, sir.

229
00:17:25,177 --> 00:17:27,372
Thanks for waiting.
Did I miss anything?

230
00:17:27,579 --> 00:17:29,137
Boss, you live in a comet.

231
00:17:29,348 --> 00:17:30,747
What's there to miss?

232
00:17:30,949 --> 00:17:32,712
Okay, then.

233
00:17:33,419 --> 00:17:34,545
What's on our agenda?

234
00:17:35,387 --> 00:17:37,480
Well, we were thinking
of taking over a planet.

235
00:17:37,689 --> 00:17:40,988
- You know, subjugating a solar system.
- Oh, no, no. I'm not in the mood.

236
00:17:41,193 --> 00:17:45,027
- Not in the mood. What else you got?
- Well, it's Christmas time, sir.

237
00:17:45,230 --> 00:17:47,130
Christmas time?

238
00:17:48,567 --> 00:17:50,899
You know what that means.

239
00:17:51,804 --> 00:17:55,467
- Time to put on snow tires?
- Time to wear long underwear.

240
00:17:55,674 --> 00:17:58,871
You know, sometimes I can't believe
we came out of the same snow drift.

